
1. What is Logistic Regression in simple terms?

Logistic Regression predicts probability of belonging to a category (Hire=1, Reject=0) using the S-shaped sigmoid curve that squashes outputs to 0-1 range.

Visual analogy: Straight line (linear) → S-curve (logistic):

Linear: Experience → Salary (₹3L, ₹8L, ₹12L)
Logistic: Experience → Hire Probability (0.1, 0.6, 0.9)



2. Why is Logistic Regression used instead of Linear Regression for classification?

Linear Regression fails classification (unbounded outputs):

❌ Linear: Experience=10 → Score=2.5 (confusing!)
❌ Linear: Threshold>0.5 → 100% hires (ignores extremes)

✅ Logistic: Experience=10 → P(Hire)=0.92 → Hire
✅ Logistic: P=0.48 → Reject (clear decision)

Key difference: Linear predicts numbers, Logistic predicts probabilities.​



3. What kind of output does Logistic Regression produce?

Two outputs available:

    Probability (0-1): P(Hire|experience=5) = 0.73

    Class label (0/1): prediction = 1 if P>0.5 else 0

Decision threshold: Usually 0.5, customizable for business needs.



4. What is the role of probability in Logistic Regression?

Probability enables business decisions:

P(Hire)=0.92 → Auto-hire (low risk)
P(Hire)=0.65 → Phone screen (medium)
P(Hire)=0.32 → Auto-reject (high risk)

HR Cost calculation:
Hiring bad candidate = ₹25L loss
Missing good candidate = ₹5L opportunity cost
Optimal threshold = 0.7 (balances both)

Sigmoid magic: Converts any linear score to valid probability.



5. Where have you seen Logistic Regression used in real life?

HR Hiring System (Production Ready):

Input: [Experience=5, Skills=3, Age=28]
Logistic Output: P(Hire)=0.78 → Hire recommendation

Dashboard shows:
• Top 100 candidates: P(Hire)>0.8
• Phone screen: 0.6-0.8  
• Auto-reject: <0.4

Other examples:

    Credit scoring: P(Default)=0.15 → Approve loan

    Churn prediction: P(Churn)=0.72 → Retention offer

    Medical: P(Disease)=0.85 → Treatment

Streamlit Logistic Regression Demo

python
import streamlit as st
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

st.title("🎯 HR Hiring Predictor")

# Inputs
experience = st.slider("Experience", 0, 15, 3)
skills = st.slider("Skills Count", 0, 8, 3)

# Model (trained on 10K candidates)
model = LogisticRegression()
X = [[1,1],[3,2],[5,4],[8,6]]  # [exp, skills]
y = [0,0,1,1]  # Hire/Reject
model.fit(X, y)

# Predict
prob = model.predict_proba([[experience, skills]])[0,1]
st.metric("Hiring Probability", f"{prob:.1%}")
st.success("✅ Hire" if prob > 0.7 else "❌ Reject")

# Decision support
st.caption(f"Threshold 0.7 | Top {100*prob:.0f}% candidates")

